courses.learning_outcomes:
Upon successful completion of this course, students should be able to:

1. integrate the conceptual foundations of public humanities with practical research skills to design community-engaged projects;
2. proficiently apply qualitative and digital research methods to document and disseminate community stories, histories, and cultural practices;
3. develop effective communication and interpersonal skills to collaborate with each other and facilitate dialogic exchanges; and
4. evaluate the ethical implications of a research, as well as demonstrate an understanding of the best practices in fostering community engagement and collaboration.

courses.required_readings:
Stuart Hall, “Cultural Identity and Diaspora” in Colonial Discourse and Post-Colonial Theory (Harvester Wheatsheaf, 1994), 222–237;
bell hooks, “Choosing the Margin: As a Space of Radical Openness,” in Yearning: Race, Gender, and Cultural Politics (South End Press, 1990), 145–153.

Terry Eagleton, “What is Ideology?” in Ideology – An Introduction (Verso, 1991), 1–25;
Louis Althusser, “Ideology and Ideological State Apparatus,” in Lenin and Philosophy and Other Essays (Monthly Review Press, 2001), 85-126;
Antonio Gramsci, Selections from the Prison Notebooks of Antonio Gramsci (ElecBook, 1999), 423-435; 481-494

Karl Marx, Capital vol. 1: Session 1 of Ch 1, “The Two Factors of the Commodity” and Ch 4;
David Harvey, The New Imperialism (Oxford UP, 2003), 87–136；

