Knowledge Incomes:
1. Basic knowledge of the philosophical issues related to the religious phenomena;
2. Basic knowledge of major theories and schools of thought in Philosophy of Religion;

Skills Incomes:
1. Understanding, analyzing and criticizing an argument philosophically.
2. Articulating one’s own argument with consistency, coherence and persuasiveness;

Attitude Incomes:
1. Respect the differences among religions, worldviews, philosophical presuppositions and cultures.
2. Being reflexive and critical to one’s own position.

Having fully engaged with the course, students are expected to have:

~ a basic familiarity with different approaches of ethics;
~ a basic knowledge of the relationships between religions and ethics;
~ an awareness of the importance of religious insights in dealing with ethical issues;
~ an ability to engage in interdisciplinary dialogues between religion and ethics.

Upon successful completion of this course, students should be able to:

Understand the issues of life and death in major religions of the world in their historical settings and contemporary contexts;
Enhance their ability to have a critical and yet sympathetic understanding and appreciation of different religious traditions;
Engage in a critical analysis of religions from doctrinal, textual and ritual perspectives.

Knowledge Outcomes:

Upon completion of the subject, students will be able to

1) understand the basic concepts of NRMs;
2) understand the basic methodological issues of NRMs;
3) understand people in NRMs. We focus on questions such as leadership, members, gender, who joins NRMs and so on

4) develop the comparative perspectives of NRMs in different countries.

Upon successful completion of this course, students should be able to:

1. Increase vocabulary and knowledge of grammar in the Arabic language;

2. Understand the usage of nominal and verbal sentences;

3. Attain a higher level of proficiency in Arabic with respect to listening, speaking, reading and writing skills in certain familiar situations.

By the end of the course, students should be able to:

1. Develop a comprehensive understanding of the musical elements which define styles, genres and historical periods of music;
2. Demonstrate cognitive, analytic and critical skills in analysing the musical works of different historical periods;
3. Gain comprehensive and in-depth understanding of the influence that cultural, social, political and religious events have exerted on music;
4. Understand pertinent education theories in music education and their implications on musical enculturation and advocacy;
5. Develop plans of introducing music through outreach activities to children and the general public by creative, play-based and other current music pedagogies such as Orff Schulwerk and Dalcroze.

